"# Chapter 15 — Making Your Own Module

Fourteen chapters in, you know enough Scheme to write your own reusable pieces. This chapter shows you how to *package* those pieces so they can be shared, reused, and gradually promoted into first-class Motoi modules.

We'll do it in three passes. First: a Scheme file that other Scheme files can pull in. Second: a folder with a proper `MANIFEST.slat`. Third: how the formal module protocol will work once the `import` verb lands.

## Pass 1 — a file of definitions

The simplest reusable unit is a file — a `.scm` file of top-level definitions. Save one as `my-utils.scm`:

```
;; my-utils.scm — shared helpers

(define (square x) (* x x))

(define (avg . nums)
  (/ (apply + nums) (length nums)))

(define (clamp x lo hi)
  (cond ((< x lo) lo)
        ((> x hi) hi)
        (else x)))

(define (make-beat frequencies)
  (for-each (lambda (f) (audio/play 'tone f 0.15)) frequencies))
```

Today, the practical way to \"pull it in\" is to concatenate. Your driver program starts with those definitions:

```
;; main.scm

;; ── my-utils.scm imported by copy ──
(define (square x) (* x x))
(define (avg . nums) (/ (apply + nums) (length nums)))
(define (clamp x lo hi)
  (cond ((< x lo) lo)
        ((> x hi) hi)
        (else x)))
(define (make-beat frequencies)
  (for-each (lambda (f) (audio/play 'tone f 0.15)) frequencies))
;; ── end my-utils.scm ──

(display (square 7)) (newline)
(display (avg 1 2 3 4 5)) (newline)
(display (clamp 15 0 10)) (newline)
(make-beat '(262 330 392))
```

Run it:

```
$ motoi run main.scm
49
3
10
ok
ok
ok
```

At the shell level, you can concatenate on demand:

```
$ cat my-utils.scm main.scm > _build.scm && motoi run _build.scm
```

That's the pragmatic pattern until `import`/`load` is fully wired. Not pretty, but it works, and it gets you to a reusable file today.

## When one file grows into many

As your library grows, keep the source split into files by topic, then concatenate them for the build:

```
my-library/
  math.scm       ← square, cube, clamp
  music.scm      ← make-beat, transpose, chord
  graphics.scm   ← draw-shape, fill-rect
  README.slat    ← what this library does
```

Build:

```
$ cat my-library/math.scm my-library/music.scm my-library/graphics.scm main.scm > _build.scm
$ motoi run _build.scm
```

Nothing formal. Just files and shell. But now you have a *structure* — a place to put the piece of a program that belongs to the piece it belongs to. When `import` lands you'll swap the `cat` command for `(import ...)` lines and delete the manual concatenation.

## Pass 2 — add a MANIFEST

Motoi modules distinguish themselves with a `MANIFEST.slat`. It's a small SLAT record naming the module and describing what it holds.

```
;; my-library/MANIFEST.slat
(manifest
  :name          \"(my-library core)\"
  :folder        \"my-library/\"
  :version       \"0.1.0\"
  :verb-count    4
  :libraries     [\"math\" \"music\" \"graphics\"]
  :depends-on    []
  :entry-modules [\"math.scm\" \"music.scm\" \"graphics.scm\"]

  :reasoning
  \"Personal helpers for a small game.\"

  :composes-with
  (\"motoi CORE\"))
```

This is the same shape Motoi's built-in modules use. It documents:
- The name others will use to refer to your module.
- The version (semver — bump when you make breaking changes).
- The list of files that make up the module.
- What it depends on.

Even before the `import` verb lands, a MANIFEST is worth writing — it's a *contract*. Someone reading your library can look at the manifest and know what they're getting.

## Pass 3 — the formal module shape (future)

When Motoi's `import` verb lands, this is what the shape will look like:

```
(import (my-library core))

(square 7)
(make-beat '(262 330 392))
```

The runtime will:
1. Resolve `(my-library core)` to a folder — `my-library/`.
2. Read `MANIFEST.slat`.
3. Load each file in `:entry-modules`.
4. Register the definitions in the current environment.
5. Return.

Idempotent — importing twice is the same as importing once.

That's the interface. Until `import` is wired, use `load` (see Pass 1) — the *effect* is the same, just less structured.

## Publishing a module (once the ecosystem exists)

The eventual plan is for Motoi modules to be discoverable through some kind of registry — pick a name, upload the folder, `import` from anywhere. That's a whole engineering effort still to come. In the meantime:

**For personal use** — keep your library in your project folder. Load with `load`.

**For sharing** — put your library on GitHub with a clear README and a version number. Ask people to clone and use `load`. Rough, but it works.

**For teams** — designate a shared folder, everyone `load`s from it. Version-control the folder.

## A worked example — a tiny fantasy console

Let's build a small game library. It'll hold a `screen`, some `sprite` helpers, and a `game-loop` macro. Save as `console/screen.scm`:

```
;; screen.scm — screen setup + clear
(define (screen-init cols rows)
  (grid-init cols rows))

(define (screen-clear)
  (grid/clear))
```

`console/sprite.scm`:

```
;; sprite.scm — helpers on top of grid/dot
(define (sprite-put col row color)
  (grid/dot col row color))

(define (sprite-line c1 r c2 color)
  (let loop ((c c1))
    (when (<= c c2)
      (grid/dot c r color)
      (loop (+ c 1)))))
```

`console/game.scm`:

```
;; game.scm — game loop
(define-syntax game-loop
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((_ n body ...)
     (let loop ((frame 0))
       (when (< frame n)
         (screen-clear)
         body ...
         (loop (+ frame 1)))))))
```

`console/MANIFEST.slat`:

```
(manifest
  :name          \"(console core)\"
  :folder        \"console/\"
  :version       \"0.1.0\"
  :verb-count    5
  :libraries     [\"screen\" \"sprite\" \"game\"]
  :entry-modules [\"screen.scm\" \"sprite.scm\" \"game.scm\"]
  :reasoning     \"A tiny fantasy console for kid-scale games.\")
```

Now a game using it — `pong.scm`. Today we still concatenate:

```
$ cat console/screen.scm console/sprite.scm console/game.scm pong.scm > _pong-build.scm
$ motoi run _pong-build.scm
```

Where `pong.scm` is:

```
(screen-init 20 12)

;; A ball that walks across.
(define ball-x 0)

(game-loop 15
  (sprite-line 0 6 20 8)         ;; the ground
  (sprite-put ball-x 5 12)       ;; the ball
  (set! ball-x (+ ball-x 1)))
```

Fifteen frames. Each frame: clear, draw the ground line, draw the ball at its current x, advance ball-x. A tiny animation from your own library.

That's a module. Written by you. Used by you. When `import` lands, one `(import (console core))` line will replace the whole concatenation.

## Rules of thumb for module design

**One purpose per file.** `screen.scm` sets up the screen. `sprite.scm` handles sprites. `game.scm` runs the loop. Don't cram everything into one file.

**Prefixes are your namespaces.** Motoi has `math/`, `audio/`, `entity/`. Your library should have `console/`, `pong/`, whatever. If your library's verbs might collide with something else, prefix them.

**Predicates end in `?`, mutation ends in `!`, conversions use `->`.** Follow the language's naming conventions. Your library will feel native.

**MANIFEST at the root of the folder.** Even if `import` isn't reading it yet, humans reading your library benefit.

**Version early.** Start at `0.1.0`. Bump the middle number for backward-compatible additions. Bump the first for breaking changes. Users appreciate the discipline.

## When you *don't* need a module

Sometimes people over-engineer. If your project is 100 lines and never grows, you don't need a folder-with-manifest. A single file is fine. Reach for modules when you have:

- More than one file's worth of code, or
- Code you want to reuse in more than one project, or
- Code you want to share with someone else.

Otherwise, keep it simple. A `.scm` file with your functions is a library. Ceremony can wait until it's earned.

## What you know now

- The simplest reusable unit is a `.scm` file loaded with `(load \"path\")`.
- As your library grows, split it into a folder with one file per topic.
- Add a `MANIFEST.slat` naming your module and listing its files.
- Future syntax `(import (my-library core))` will replace multiple `load` calls once the loader lands.
- Naming conventions: `?` for predicates, `!` for mutations, `->` for conversions, `/` for module namespace.
- Version early: start at `0.1.0`, bump appropriately.
- Don't over-engineer. Reach for modules only when the code earns them.

## Try before you turn the page

1. Split your Chapter 10 beat DSL into a file `beats/kits.scm` (with `kick`, `snare`, `hat` macros) and `beats/step.scm` (with `step`, `pattern`). Load both in a driver file. Play a pattern.

2. Write a small `sprites/` module: `sprite-square col row size color` (draws a filled square), `sprite-line c r len color` (draws a horizontal line). MANIFEST it. Use it in a demo.

3. Design a `words/` module that maps common named colors to color numbers: `(color-of 'red)` returns 8, `(color-of 'blue)` returns 12. Provide 6-8 named colors. Use `assoc` internally.

4. Take a favorite CORE verb and *wrap* it in your own module with a friendlier name. For example, `(paint c r)` inside `paint/simple.scm` should call `(grid/dot c r 10)` under the hood.

5. Package your best animation from any earlier chapter as a loadable module. Name the file. Write a MANIFEST. Ship it (mentally, if not literally).

## What's next

Chapter 16: **show and tell**. The final chapter — a full demo scene that pulls everything together. Music, motion, entities, physics, cortex, macros. The kind of thing you can send to a friend and say *here — I made this in Motoi Scheme, and I understand every line*.")
